[04:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'less attention, but makes so much sense when you think about it is journalism and documentary. Surprisingly, it\'s been some of the larger publications that have jumped straight into radiance fields. At The New Yorker, visual features editor Sam Wolson has been using Gaussian splatting on multiple'

[04:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'published projects going back nearly a year. His first published story was for portrait of artist Lorna Simpson for the magazine\'s New York-themed anniversary issue. And I met up with Sam shortly after its publication to talk about Gaussian splatting.'

[04:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'For him, it\'s allowed him to expand his role as a journalist to become both a director, cinematographer, editor, in addition to also covering the story. Sam returned to Gaussian splatting yet again to profile a mother and daughter leaving the United States. And through it, he'

[05:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'created a specific camera motions to sync up with the reader\'s scrolling to help bring the audience closer to the story. It\'s a super impactful story and I really recommend you guys check it out. His most recent project showcased a bit of Gaussian splatting\'s versatility by using it to help accompany a'

[05:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'restaurant review, providing lifelike 3D reconstructions of the food at E Cavallini. Another major publication, The New York Times R&amp;D team has been actively exploring the various radiance field representations, beginning with NeRF a few years ago, and has continued'

[05:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to publish their notes with Gaussian splatting. They\'ve posted guides on how to capture data for radiance field, how they could do spatial journalism using their own in-house method Three Bird. And I was even fortunate enough to do a couple of panels with A.J. Shavar from their team last year, who has been'

[05:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'posting his own experiences with Gaussian Splatting. At the beginning of this year, a documentary called Out of the Ashes about the Palisades and Eaton fires in Los Angeles began to show excerpts of their work. Their team used Gaussian Splatting to directly confront audiences with the'

[06:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'aftermath of the tragedy. I interviewed much of the crew and with more information about the project expected later this year, it stands as a stark reminder that this medium captures all moments in time, including some of the most devastating moments that people'

[06:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have to endure. &gt;&gt; I know sometimes that can be difficult to visualize, so we want to show you what that would look like and &gt;&gt; And in case you thought that simulation and media entertainment don\'t have any overlap, here\'s a fun little example of a company that\'s using Gaussian'

[06:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Splatting and it\'s actually The Weather Channel. The Weather Channel has a technology called Flood Effects and Flood Effects is powered by Gaussian Splatting. And basically, the use case is super simple. They take a drone, they fly around an affected region,'

[06:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reconstruct it and then simulate floods in that area. &gt;&gt; completely submerged on that first level and it\'s also filling some of these pools and what\'s more concerning though is what is potentially in that water. We\'re talking'

[06:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; This is on the air. You can actually see the Gaussians directly in the broadcast too and they actually were the first company won an Emmy for Gaussian Splatting. &gt;&gt; And the Emmy goes to Flood X Florida storms and area'

