VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The Weather Channel &gt;&gt; In 2023, The Weather Channel developed an innovative technical execution Flood FX. This creative approach visualizes potential tropical storm surge in a realistic 3D live rendering of a'

[07:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'specific local area depicting the real-time data from the National Hurricane Center. &gt;&gt; Startup Grecia has been making dynamic Gaussian Splatting more tangible in a couple different ways. Just this last week, they launched a 4D Gaussian Splatting experience at the Port'

[07:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Aventura theme park in Spain whereby park goers can actually see a mixed reality demo of a scientist through Unity plugin. However, this actually was not the first time that Gracia has explored doing these in-person experiences. Last fall, their team'

[07:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually put on a mixed reality fashion show using Gaussian splatting in the United Kingdom where the audience members were all wearing VR headsets and witnessed a synced reconstruction of models walking down the runway. Continuing on with the theme of art, you'

[07:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'might not know this, but one of the most popular museums in Los Angeles, LACMA, directly in your browser, you can check out spirits from John Gerrard, which uses Gaussian splatting to convey discarded footwear found on beaches all around the world. In the traditional'

[08:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video game world, I am aware of quite a few large studios that are currently using Gaussian splatting, but video games also suffer from the same problem as film where the lead times are so long that we don\'t actually get to see the results until long after they were'

[08:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'initially used. That said, platforms like PlayCanvas have been shipping a ton of updates to make creating video game style experiences easier, such as walking mode, as this PlayCanvas employee detailed out exactly how they made this. However, if you want to make'

[08:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Gaussian splatting video games even easier, there is a platform called Arrival Space that lets you vibe code directly on top of Gaussian splatting and use things like 3JS to create playable experiences. You can add things like physics, objects, you can relight'

[08:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scenes, and produce multiplayer environments. I am working on a separate video to go a bit more in-depth into Arrival Space and vibe coding directly on top of Gaussian splatting because you actually can create some really cool experiences directly from real world locations and captures. Part of what'

[08:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually motivated me to make this video today was seeing Ren\'s video earlier this week from Quarter Digital where basically he was just showcasing dynamic Gaussian splatting and talking about some of the places that Gaussian splatting was going to pop up, but I would very much recommend that people'

[09:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'watch Ren\'s video if you haven\'t seen it already, although I think it would be much more likely that you\'ve seen his video than you\'ve seen any of my content before. All these examples so far have been normal on-land capture, but, you know, can it work underwater? And yeah, it can'

[09:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually, and this is where we\'re starting to see marine biologists using Gaussian splatting to reconstruct coral reefs to do examination, to study them, to see how they progress and change over time. And it\'s serving as a really'

[09:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'valuable way for them to understand a physical space even if that space isn\'t on land. The simulation and robotics industry has been one of the biggest benefactors of advancements within radiance fields. This is because they can help close what\'s known as the'

[09:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'domain gap. While it would be possible to handcraft life-like 3D scenes for robots to be simulated, this would take highly skilled employees a long time just to make a single scene. Now Gaussian splatting is helping companies ingest 2D images and the sensors around'

[10:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the vehicles to be simulated in life-like 3D in a fraction of the time. To better illustrate why this is the case, here\'s a quick clip from a conversation I had with the CEO of 3rd Dimension AI\'s Tolga Kart. &gt;&gt; It helps that, you know, we can go from'

[10:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from a recorded footage from a robot to your running in simulation in then under 2 hours. I think that\'s also very, very compelling as an offering. The whole'

[10:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'idea here is to make sure a robot can tell it\'s in a simulated world, right? So, it\'s the same. It\'s just you\'re feeding in videos from different views. You\'re generating novel views to get the robot to operate in this 3D world. And'

[10:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ideally, it cannot tell that this is different from the footage it saw in the real world. &gt;&gt; This utilization ranges from the smallest companies all the way up to Nvidia. &gt;&gt; Gaussian splats. Just in case. &gt;&gt; Which actually has added Gaussian'

[10:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'splatting support to both Isaac Sim and Omniverse through 3D Gaussian Unscented Transform, which is a variant of Gaussian splatting that the Nvidia team published. And the Unscented Transform is honestly one of the most underrated representations out there because it\'s'

[11:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'also what powers Alpha Sim, which is part of Alpha Male, Nvidia\'s self-driving framework, and it plays a major role in Neurae, their neural reconstruction library, which is how Nvidia refers to radiance fields. And if you\'ve been paying close attention to'

[11:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'open-source libraries like G Splat, you\'ll also notice an extreme uptick in contributions from the Nvidia team directly over the last month or so, and I don\'t think that\'s a coincidence, and I think we\'re actually going to see quite a lot more information directly from Nvidia about some of these'

[11:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'libraries. While While splatting has been exciting to many industries from my view, maybe no other industry has been quite as excited about Gaussian Splatting as the construction and geospatial industries. And I can understand why.'

[11:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Despite these being two large industries that are very familiar with 3D, they\'ve always had a problem with photogrammetry when they would try to reconstruct things like thin structures, reflective surfaces, vegetation, and glass. However, Gaussian Splatting solves all these problems right away. And on top of'

[11:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it, most of the existing photogrammetry data can be reprocessed without needing to be reshot, meaning that they could suddenly see the world as it occurs. For these industries, this is a massive win. Remember, as opposed to photogrammetry, Gaussian Splatting is a method to'

[12:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reconstruct a radiance field. While Gaussian Splatting has been criticized for its lack of precise measurement capabilities compared to photogrammetry, Esri did announce at GeoWeek this year that they had solved the shrinking bias and are getting survey grade measurements directly from splats. Now,'

[12:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'let\'s talk about the construction industry specifically. While it might sound trivial, one use case of construction has been to verify existing conditions on job sites. This used to mean taking individual images, videos, or 360 captures, but none of them really'

[12:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'gave a complete picture of the job site. Now, with Gaussian Splatting, teams are just simply walking through sites with potentially the same hardware, and then processing them into splats. Because Gaussian Splatting can be shared from a single URL and rendered on devices going'

[12:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all the way down to Apple TVs, distributing these captures is fast, it\'s accurate, and it also gives a lifelike overview of a given job site to an entire team. It\'s not as known outside of the construction industry, but flying drones underneath cranes is'

[12:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'extremely dangerous. Here, Gaussian Splatting supports these construction teams by allowing them to rapidly capture and document things like pre-pours and slabs with just a handheld scanner. They\'re also using the reconstructions as a better way to communicate to their clients and'

[13:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stakeholders what the location will look like, and it\'s actually working. One of the ways they\'re doing this is that they\'re placing synthetic cameras all around their BIM models, reconstructing that, and then dropping them into a larger reconstruction of the surrounding neighborhood. Then, you can also take'

[13:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'things up a notch. And the way they\'re doing this is by layering captures on top of one another over time, and you can essentially make a lifelike 4D time-lapse of the construction site\'s progress thanks to platforms like Gazela Pro. But, it goes even deeper than that.'

[13:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, construction teams are capturing at various milestones and can actually track in photorealistic capacity what\'s behind walls. This means that as locations require maintenance over time, their teams can objectively reference'

[13:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what is placed behind the walls, and they are literally doing this right now. What\'s also beginning to happen is the merging of Gaussian Splatting with AI. While vanilla Gaussian Splatting is not AI, it is very well suited to be leveraged by AI. This means things like'

[13:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'auto segmentation and labeling, but the ceiling of where we will see this go by the end of 2026 will be significantly higher, and that\'s unfortunately all I can say about this for right now. I actually was speaking recently with a'

[14:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'friend in the construction industry who told me that they had been given just a small amount of time to inspect a potential client site. So, they actually brought a Xgrid\'s camera with them, spent the time they did have on site actually just capturing, and then when they returned home, they just'

[14:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reconstructed the space in its entirety and no longer needed to rush through taking down all the information. They told me that it helped them dramatically get more accurate measurements on the site and pass along all that information to their subcontractor for bids. They ended up winning the bid for the site,'

[14:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and I\'ve been hearing stories like this more and more often. In the two industries we\'re seeing active embracing of Gaussian Splatting led by companies like Esri, Bentley Systems who acquired Cesium, DJI who added Gaussian Splatting support to both Terra and Flight Hub, Niantic with their newly relaunched'

[14:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Scaniverse, and Xgrid\'s whose spatial cameras have been popping up everywhere. And one industry that is heavily beginning to use Xgrid\'s cameras is the real estate industry. And it makes a lot of sense as to why this industry would be so interested in Gaussian Splatting, and we\'re seeing it from the very top of'

[14:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the industry. So, companies like Zillow and CoStar Group are already working with Gaussian Splatting. And here\'s actually a fun fact, one of the Zillow engineers is actually the developer behind Metal Splatter, which is a Gaussian Splatting VR application for the Apple Vision Pro. Zillow has'

[15:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'something called Sky Tour where certain showcase listings are explorable properties. However, they are only exterior captures for the time being. And on the other side, we have the CoStar Group, which owns homes.com, they own apartments.com, and they even own'

[15:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Matterport. And they have also been adding Gaussian splatting support, too. Their implementation takes on the Matterport name as just Matterport 3D exteriors, and I think it\'s very likely that we\'re going to see both of these companies really start to step up the Gaussian splatting presence, potentially'

[15:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'start offering interiors, too. When we talk about interiors, you probably already know what I\'m going to say. I covered it in one of my first videos, but for all the people asking when Gaussian splatting will be coming to Google Maps, the answer is about 3 years ago. But they actually don\'t use'

[15:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Gaussian splatting, but rather Google\'s own version, which is called Rad Splat. It\'s a hybrid Nerf and Gaussian splatting pipeline that they use to power their interior immersive view. If you\'re curious about it, I would definitely recommend to check out my'

[16:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'full video on it. And if you\'ve been paying close attention to my Gaussian splatting job board, you may have also noticed that Apple has had several job listings over the last couple of years explicitly saying that they want Gaussian splatting engineers to build a'

[16:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'very lifelike version of Apple Maps. And while Apple is one of the most secretive companies on Earth, they\'ve given us another example of Gaussian splatting that is right in front of our faces. Apple doesn\'t often comment on exactly what technology they use. They refer to'

[16:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'AI as Apple Intelligence, XR as spatial computing, but Apple was explicit last October in saying that Gaussian splatting is the technology behind both personas and spatial photos. Additionally, so many people were'

[16:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'exposed to Gaussian splatting through Apple\'s single image method sharp at the end of 2025. With WWDC just a couple months away, if Apple does not show more Gaussian splatting things there, I would truly be surprised. While not explicitly'

[16:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in the real estate world, we have also seen two versions of Gaussian splatting from Meta in both Hyperscape and Hyperscape Capture. The latter of which allows you to capture stunning 3D directly from your Quest headset. And though they recently scaled back some of'

[17:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the features like sharing spaces with people, the team at Meta have clearly figured out how to get high-fidelity 3D on cameras that maybe weren\'t meant to do so. And look, these are just a couple of public examples that I can show just'

[17:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'now. And there is so much more that\'s happening behind the scenes that\'s going to be coming out later this year from some of the world\'s largest companies in addition to some of the startups, too. But I can\'t share them obviously just yet without getting in an extreme amount'

[17:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of trouble. And I do promise you though, what is coming will transform the way that we both create and interact with content in our lives. We\'re now beginning to see a glimpse into the generalized amount of industries that are beginning to understand that they'

[17:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can do their work in life-like 3D. And while many of the examples that I showed today are just normal Gaussian splatting, I think that it is extremely likely that we\'re going to see alternative representations that build on top of some of the research that'

[17:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we\'ve seen so far. So whether it is Gaussian splatting or if it\'s Nerf or it\'s a voxel-based or ray-tracing-based approach or something that\'s fundamentally different, I think that one thing that is very consistent is that life-like 3D imaging as a medium is here to stay. And for me, this is what'

[18:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'m most excited about more than anything. It\'s what I hope to bring content to all of you about on a more regular basis. And so, with all that in mind, if you found anything new or interesting from today\'s video, I would'

